# Data Archival Standards

This document defines standards for long-term data storage, format selection, metadata requirements, and access control for research data.

---

## Core Principle: Data Must Outlive the Project

Research data must remain accessible and interpretable for at least 10 years after the project ends, independent of the original software, hardware, or team.

---

## Storage Tiers

### Tier Classification

| Tier | Retention | Access Frequency | Storage Class | Example |
|------|-----------|------------------|---------------|---------|
| Hot | Active project | Daily | SSD, local NVMe | Working datasets |
| Warm | 1-3 years | Monthly | Object storage (S3 Standard) | Completed experiment data |
| Cold | 3-10 years | Yearly | Object storage (S3 Glacier) | Archived datasets |
| Archive | 10+ years | Rarely | Tape, institutional repository | Published dataset snapshots |

### Storage Selection Rules

| Data Type | Recommended Tier | Rationale |
|-----------|-----------------|-----------|
| Raw experimental data | Warm -> Cold | Must be preserved for reproduction |
| Processed / intermediate | Hot -> delete | Can be regenerated from raw + code |
| Final results | Warm -> Archive | Referenced by publications |
| Model checkpoints | Hot -> Cold | Large, can be retrained if needed |
| Logs and metadata | Warm | Needed for debugging / audit |

---

## Format Selection

### Preferred Formats (Open, Self-Describing)

| Data Type | Preferred Format | Avoid | Rationale |
|-----------|-----------------|-------|-----------|
| Tabular data | Parquet, CSV | Excel (.xlsx) | Open, schema-embedded (Parquet) |
| Time series | Parquet, HDF5 | Pickle | Columnar, efficient |
| Images | PNG (lossless), TIFF | BMP, proprietary RAW | Open, widely supported |
| Text | UTF-8 plain text, JSON | Word (.docx) | Human-readable, open |
| Structured data | JSON, YAML | XML (if avoidable) | Readable, well-tooled |
| Multidimensional arrays | NetCDF, HDF5, Zarr | NumPy .npy | Self-describing, metadata |
| Model weights | ONNX, SafeTensors | Pickle | Portable, secure |
| Geospatial | GeoParquet, GeoTIFF | Shapefile | Modern, efficient |

### Format Anti-Patterns

| Pattern | Risk | Alternative |
|---------|------|-------------|
| Python pickle files | Security risk, Python-version dependent | Parquet, JSON, SafeTensors |
| Proprietary formats | Vendor lock-in, may become unreadable | Convert to open format |
| Compressed without manifest | Cannot inspect without decompressing | Parquet (built-in compression) |
| Format without schema | Interpretation depends on external docs | Self-describing formats |

